2. Salesforce Best Practices

1. Never write SOQL queries inside loops.
2. Never perform DML operations inside loops.
3. Always bulkify your code to handle multiple records (up to 200).
4. Query only the fields you actually need.
5. Query data once and reuse it instead of querying repeatedly.
6. Use Set to remove duplicates and collect unique IDs.
7. Use Map for fast record lookups instead of nested loops.
8. Process records in collections (List, Set, Map), not one by one.
9. Avoid nested loops whenever possible to improve performance.
10. Move heavy processing to asynchronous Apex (Queueable, Batch, Future).
11. Use a Trigger Handler framework—keep triggers logic-free.
12. Keep only one trigger per object.
13. Write reusable business logic in helper/service classes.
14. Avoid hardcoding IDs, URLs, or values—use Custom Metadata or Custom Settings.
15. Use constants instead of repeating literal values throughout the code.
16. Handle exceptions using try-catch where appropriate.
17. Always write unit tests with meaningful assertions.
18. Avoid recursive trigger execution by implementing recursion control.
19. Use selective SOQL queries to improve query performance.
20. Monitor governor limits using the Limits class during development.
21. Use Database methods (Database.insert, Database.update, etc.) when partial success is required.
22. Follow the Single Responsibility Principle—each class should have one purpose.
23. Keep methods small, readable, and reusable.
24. Use meaningful class, method, and variable names.
25. Write comments only when they add value; let clean code explain itself.
26. Always consider governor limits while designing your solution, not after writing the code.



3. Relationships

I.   Lookup Relationship
II.  Master-Detail Relationship
III. Many-to-Many Relationship (using a Junction Object)

1. Lookup Relationship
------------------------------------------------------------

Definition
- A loose relationship between two objects.
- The child record can exist without a parent.
- Parent and child are independent.

Characteristics
- Parent record is optional (unless marked Required).
- Deleting the parent does NOT delete the child.
- Each object has its own Owner.
- Separate Sharing and Security.
- Roll-Up Summary fields are NOT supported.
- Maximum 40 Lookup relationships per object.

Example
Account (Parent)
    ↑
Contact (Child)

A Contact may or may not be linked to an Account.

Another Example
Employee --> Manager

An employee can have a manager, but the employee record still exists even if the manager record is deleted.

II. Master-Detail Relationship
------------------------------------------------------------

Definition
- A tightly coupled relationship.
- Child record cannot exist without the parent.

Characteristics
- Parent is mandatory.
- Deleting the parent automatically deletes all child records.
- Child inherits Owner from Parent.
- Child inherits Sharing and Security.
- Roll-Up Summary fields are supported.
- Maximum 2 Master-Detail relationships per object.

Example
Account (Master)
    ↑
Invoice (Detail)

If the Account is deleted, all related Invoices are also deleted.

Another Example
Order (Master)
    ↑
Order Line Item (Detail)

Deleting the Order deletes all Order Line Items.


III. Many-to-Many Relationship
------------------------------------------------------------

Definition
- Allows multiple records of one object to be related to multiple records of another object.

How it is created
- By using a Junction Object.
- The Junction Object contains two Master-Detail relationships.

Example

Student
   ↑
Enrollment (Junction Object)
   ↓
Course

One Student can enroll in many Courses.
One Course can have many Students.

Example Data

Student A -> Java
Student A -> Apex
Student B -> Apex
Student B -> LWC

Iv. 4. Self Relationship
------------------------------------------------------------

Definition
- An object has a relationship with itself.
- Implemented using a Lookup Relationship.

Example

Employee
   ↑
Manager (Employee)

OR

Account
   ↑
Parent Account

A company can have another company as its parent.

V. Hierarchical Relationship
------------------------------------------------------------

Definition
- Special relationship available ONLY on the User object.

Characteristics
- User can reference another User.
- Used to define organizational hierarchy.

Example

CEO
 ↑
Manager
 ↑
Employee

Every Employee can have a Manager.


=====================================================================

Lookup vs Master-Detail
------------------------------------------------------------

Parent Required?
Lookup          : No
Master-Detail   : Yes

Child Exists Without Parent?
Lookup          : Yes
Master-Detail   : No

Delete Parent
Lookup          : Child remains
Master-Detail   : Child is deleted

Owner
Lookup          : Separate Owner
Master-Detail   : Child inherits Parent Owner

Sharing
Lookup          : Separate
Master-Detail   : Inherited from Parent

Roll-Up Summary
Lookup          : Not Supported
Master-Detail   : Supported

Maximum per Object
Lookup          : 40
Master-Detail   : 2


